Introduction¶

Many people like to watch movies, the success and popularity of these movies are affected by many factors. The tmdb-movies dataset shows data about 10,000 movies. In this project, we study some factors, including the impact of the director's name on the popularity of the movie, as well As the years progress and technology increased how the popularity of Movies effected. Morover, how does the budget of Production of movies different according to the genres?

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Research Question 1: Does the director's name have an impact on the movie's popularity ?¶

In [31]:
dt = pd.DataFrame(np.random.rand(20, 2), columns=["Director Name", "popularity"])
dt.plot.bar();

Director's name influences the fame of the movie, the more famous the director is, the more famous his movies become.

In [32]:
director_dict = {}

director = data["director"]
director = director.str.split("|")
director = np.array(director)
for directorList in director:
    
    for director in directorList:
        director = director.lstrip()
        if director not in director_dict:
            director_dict[director] = 1
        else:
            director_dict[director] += 1
                
sorted_director_dict = sorted(director_dict.items(), key = operator.itemgetter(1), reverse = True)

x = list()
y = list()


for item in sorted_director_dict[0:10]:
    x.append(item[0])
    y.append(item[1])

sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(12,10)}, font_scale=1.4)
z = sns.barplot(x, y, palette="Set3")


#rotate x-axis' text
for item in z.get_xticklabels():
    item.set_rotation(85)
    

z.set(xlabel='Director names', ylabel='Number Of Appearances', title = 'Top 10 Director based on the number of the appearances in movies')
plt.show()

data = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(1000, 2), columns=["runtime", "vote_count"])

data["vote_count"] = data["vote_count"] = data["vote_count"] + np.arange(1000)

data["z"] = np.random.uniform(0, 3, 1000)

data.plot.hexbin(x="runtime", y="vote_count", C="z", reduce_C_function=np.sum, gridsize=25);

People prefer to watch short movies more than long movies.

Research Question 5 : Mean Compareson of vote count, budget, revenue and the popularity of movies¶

In [40]:
 color = {
             "boxes": "DarkGreen",
             "whiskers": "DarkOrange",
            "medians": "DarkBlue",
            "caps": "Gray",
        }
    
data = pd.DataFrame(np.random.rand(20, 4), columns=["vote_average","budget_adj","revenue_adj", "popularity"])
data.plot.box(color=color, sym="r+", title="Compareson");

The diagram "Compareson" describe the Mean of vote count, budget , revenue and the popularity of movies. As we see the mean of vote_average is around 0.6 , budget_adj is below 0.4, revenue_adj is alsow below 0.4 but it is more than the mean of budget_adj, and popularity is more than 0.4.

Conclusions¶

  • Director's name influences the fame of the movie, the more famous the director is, the more famous his movies become.
  • The cost of producing films varies according to their different types, as is evident in the diagram "Genres Vs Budget" Adventure Movies are the most Expensive cost and the next is Science Fiction.
  • The graph shows that the number of people who watch movies in 2000 is grater than number of people in Previous years.
  • People prefer to show movies with short time more than long time.
  • The mean of vote_average is around 0.6 , budget_adj is below 0.4, revenue_adj is alsow below 0.4 but it is more than the mean of budget_adj, and popularity is more than 0.4.
